CENTERED	0001	557	1769	1604	1801	Descriptions of New Carboniferous FOSSILS from the Western States. 
CENTERED	0001	769	1836	1390	1864	BY F. B. MEEK AND A. H. WORTHEN&gt; 
CENTERED	0001	823	1875	1334	1901	Of the Illinois State Geological Survey. 
CENTERED	0001	899	1925	1272	1953	ECHINODKRMATA. 
CENTERED	0001	818	1985	1343	2016	Genus POTERIOGRINITES, Miller. 
CENTERED	0001	534	2041	1663	2074	The typical forms of this genus have a more or less obconical body, with a 
CENTERED	0001	500	2076	1662	2108	protuberant base, strong rounded column, and generally long&gt; stout, bifur-
CENTERED	0001	502	2107	1664	2141	cating arms&gt; always composed each of a single series of pieces. The body is 
CENTERED	0001	504	2189	1665	2221	composed of five basal pieces, alternating with five subradials, and five first 
CENTERED	0001	501	2220	1663	2254	radials, all alternating with the latter, excepting one on the anal side, which 
CENTERED	0001	500	2255	1528	2287	rests directly upon the upper truncated edge of one of the subradials. 
CENTERED	0001	533	2287	1667	2321	The anal series consists, normally, of two alternating vertical ranges of 
CENTERED	0001	499	2320	1662	2354	pieces&gt; the lowest piece of which rests between the upper sloping sides of two 
CENTERED	0001	500	2354	1664	2387	of the subradials, partly under one side of the first radial on the right, and 
CENTERED	0001	501	2389	1663	2421	connects above its middle, on the left, with another resting on the upper 
CENTERED	0001	498	2421	1663	2453	truncated edge of one of the subradials, and joining the first radial on the left, 
CENTERED	0001	498	2453	1664	2486	while usually one or two more above these connect with others belonging 
CENTERED	0001	497	2488	1663	2519	more properly to the base of the so-called proboscis. The primary radials 
CENTERED	0001	499	2519	1663	2553	above the first are free, and generally smaller&gt; and vary in number in the dif-
CENTERED	0001	500	2552	1664	2585	ferent rays of the same individual, from about two to eight, ten, twelve or 
CENTERED	0001	500	2586	1664	2618	more, below the first bifurcation. The ventral part of tbe body is produced 
CENTERED	0001	501	2619	1664	2653	upward in the form of a cylindrical, or more or less expanded proboscis (so 
CENTERED	0001	502	2651	1664	2684	called), generally as wide as the whole space between the arms below, and 
CENTERED	0001	501	2686	1664	2717	composed of regular hexagonal pieces, often with pores passing through the 
CENTERED	0001	502	2719	1663	2750	sutures between. The opening is said to be near the top of the proboscis, 
CENTERED	0001	500	2750	1663	2784	though we have never seen it in any of the numerous specimens we have ex-
CENTERED	0001	499	2783	613	2807	amined. 
CENTERED	0001	534	2837	1662	2870	In addition to the species agreeing in all respects with the characters above 
CENTERED	0001	501	2870	1663	2903	given, there are numerous others which, although conforming in general 
CENTERED	0001	500	2905	1664	2936	structure with the typical forms, still depart so widely in some of their char-
CENTERED	0001	500	2937	1664	2968	acters, that when the extremes are compared, it seems difficult to believe that 
CENTERED	0001	499	2969	1662	3001	they can all belong to one genus. And yet they are all linked together by so 
CENTERED	0001	500	3002	1663	3033	many intermediate gradations that, in the present stirte of our knowledge of these 
CENTERED	0001	499	3035	1661	3067	fossils, we are at a loss to see how they can be separated more than subgene-
CENTERED	0001	499	3068	1664	3100	rically. For some of these types the names <i>Seaphioerinus, Zeaerinus, Ceelioerinns, </i>
CENTERED	0001	499	3102	1662	3133	etc.i have been proposed, either as subgenera or as distinct genera from <i>Pote-</i>
CENTERED	0001	499	3135	1663	3166	<i>rioerinifes. </i>Adopting the former view, these groups may, in order to facilitate 
CENTERED	0001	498	3167	1627	3198	their study, be arranged as follows, commencing with <i>Poteriocrinites </i>proper: 
CENTERED	0001	500	3208	1016	3239	1.â€” Genus PorsniocRINITss, Miller.

CENTERED	0011	533	2072	1662	2103	In the second volume of the Illinois Reports, published in 1866, after admit-
CENTERED	0011	499	2104	1661	2136	ting as distinct genera from <i>Actinoerinites </i>the groups <i>3fegtstoerinust Agaricoeri-</i>
CENTERED	0011	500	2137	1663	2169	<i>nus, Amphoracrinus </i>and some others, we also separated under the name <i>Stroto-</i>
CENTERED	0011	500	2169	1662	2200	<i>crinus </i>a group of remarkable American Carboniferous species, of which <i>Aeti-</i>
CENTERED	0011	500	2202	1662	2233	<i>nocr. perumbrosus, </i>Hall, was regarded as the type. At the same time that we 
CENTERED	0011	499	2234	1663	2265	made this separation there were amongst the collections before us specimens 
CENTERED	0011	498	2266	1661	2298	of another allied type, in regard to the proper disposition of which we were in 
CENTERED	0011	499	2299	1661	2330	considerable doubt. These belong to the group of which <i>A. ventricosust </i>Hall, 
CENTERED	0011	501	2331	1665	2362	may be regarded as an example. We readily observed that while in some of 
CENTERED	0011	499	2363	1659	2395	their characters they agree most nearly with <i>Strotoerinus, </i>that in others they 
CENTERED	0011	498	2396	1662	2428	seemed to be more closely allied to <i>Actinocrtnites, </i>and at one time we were 
CENTERED	0011	498	2428	1661	2460	very much inclined to the opinion that a strictly systematic definitio of all the 
CENTERED	0011	498	2460	1662	2492	different genera of the Crinoidea would require their separation as a distinct 
CENTERED	0011	497	2493	1661	2526	intermediate genus. Wishing to avoid disturbing the existing nomenclature, 
CENTERED	0011	496	2526	1662	2558	however, as much as possible, we finally concluded to place this group pro-
CENTERED	0011	497	2558	1126	2589	visionally as a section under <i>Aetinoerinites. </i>
CENTERED	0011	533	2591	1666	2623	Since that time we have had an opportunity to study an extensive series of 
CENTERED	0011	499	2624	1662	2656	these and the allied groups, in llIr. Wachsmuth's collection, and have been led 
CENTERED	0011	497	2656	1663	2688	to the conclusion that if this type does not form a separate genus, holding an 
CENTERED	0011	496	2689	1662	2720	intermediate position between <i>Strotocrinus </i>and <i>Aetinocrinites, </i>that it should be 
CENTERED	0011	497	2721	1662	2753	placed as a distinct subgenus under the former. Adopting this view, and ad-
CENTERED	0011	497	2754	1662	2786	mitting, as we have elsewhere done, that the <i>Batoerinus </i>and <i>Dorycrinus </i>groups 
CENTERED	0011	498	2786	1663	2818	should stand as distinct genera, the genus <i>Aetinocrinites would </i>be left to include
